{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638749"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17734"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17734"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.56,0,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74912"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10448"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60410"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"9511"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24397"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74912"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a long-term history of joint pain in her hands, including the distal interphalangeal joints, and her knees. The pain is described as deep, aching, and poorly localised. It has been worsening throughout its course. She reports a progressive loss of movement and crepitus in the affected joints. Over time, she has experienced pain at rest and at night. She has no history of recent falls. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatoid arthritis","Osteoarthritis","Gout","Psoriatic arthritis","Systemic lupus erythematosus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E, which commonly affects the distal interphalangeal joints and the knees. The deep, aching pain, crepitus, and progressive loss of movement are characteristic of osteoarthritis. Pain at rest and at night can occur as the condition progresses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with symmetrical joint involvement, morning stiffness, and sparing of the distal interphalangeal joints, making it less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E presents with acute, episodic attacks of joint pain, often affecting the first metatarsophalangeal joint, rather than chronic pain in the distal interphalangeal joints and knees.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can affect the distal interphalangeal joints but is often associated with skin changes of psoriasis, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause joint pain but usually presents with other systemic symptoms and does not commonly affect the distal interphalangeal joints.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteoarthritis commonly affects the distal interphalangeal joints and is characterised by deep, aching joint pain and crepitus.","Rheumatoid arthritis spares the distal interphalangeal joints and presents with symmetrical joint involvement and morning stiffness."],"references":["Hunter DJ, Felson DT. Osteoarthritis. BMJ. 2006 Mar 18;332(7542):639-42. doi: 10.1136/bmj.332.7542.639. PMID: 16543327; PMCID: PMC1403209.","Loeser RF, Goldring SR, Scanzello CR, Goldring MB. Osteoarthritis: a disease of the joint as an organ. Arthritis Rheum. 2012 Jun;64(6):1697-707. doi: 10.1002/art.34453. Epub 2012 Mar 5. PMID: 22392533; PMCID: PMC3366018.","Sinusas K. Osteoarthritis: diagnosis and treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2012 Jan 1;85(1):49-56. Erratum in: Am Fam Physician. 2012 Nov 15;86(10):893. PMID: 22230308.","Jang S, Lee K, Ju JH. Recent Updates of Diagnosis, Pathophysiology, and Treatment on Osteoarthritis of the Knee. Int J Mol Sci. 2021 Mar 5;22(5):2619. doi: 10.3390/ijms22052619. PMID: 33807695; PMCID: PMC7961389."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60410"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17734"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60410"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T09:57:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T09:57:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10448"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74912"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\